1. Business Understanding¶

The dataset used in this implementation of a wide and deep network consists of 28 categorical and numeric features collected on 5,043 national and international movies.

This implementation of a wide and deep network has application in the global film industry, which is on track to becoming a 50 billion dollar industry by 2020. Current projections place gross box office revenues to increase by 12 billion dollars over the next 2 years[1], which makes this a possibly lucrative industry to invest in.

Contrary to popular belief, roughly 49% of Hollywood movies lose money, leaving just above half returning a profit. Taking a closer look at some movie profitability statistics, 11% of movies made a profit equivalent to more than twice their original budget, 11% made a profit equal to between 100% and 200% of their original budget, 28% made a profit equal to less than their budget, 34% lost the equivalent of less than their budget, 9% lost between 100% and 200% of their budget, and 7% lost more than twice the value of their budget[2].

As studios, investors, and producers, invest millions of dollars into movies every year with hopes of profit, seeing a return on their investment is surprisingly roughly 50/50. As an investor in any industry, a guarantee to see a return on your investment is often not realistic, however a statistical chance that one would receive return on their investment would help investors in deciding whether to invest their money or not.

The purpose of this wide and deep network implementation is to predict a movie's profitability, before the film is made. Thus, giving movie investors a probabilistic sense of how likely it is that their movie will be profitable.

The classification task of this wide and deep network is to predict whether a movie will gross more or less than its original budget.

The current benchmark this algorithm would need to beat is the the percentage of films that return profit in Hollywood today, which is 51%. Furthermore, for this algorithm to be successful and deployable, it needs to be achieve accuracy greater than the current industry standard at 51% (which I will refer to as the 'current industry standard' for the sake of this lab and exercise) and inherently weary of false positives, which would cause certain loss of money to those involved.

[1] https://www.statista.com/topics/964/film/

[2] https://stephenfollows.com/hollywood-movies-make-a-profit/

2.1.2 Evaluating Data Quality¶

Before going any further with the data preparation, let's investigate the quality of the dataset. In checking the data quality, I will look for both missing and duplicated entries. Firstly, to check if the dataset has any missing values, I will use the built-in package missingno, which gives an illustrative matrix representation of the completeness of the dataset.

In [5]:
mn.matrix(df)

As seen in the missingno matrix above, the dataset contains some missing values. The decision in whether to impute the missing values or to drop them from the dataset is simple when considering the vast number of missing entries in the gross column. Since the gross column is used to derive the target variable for this classification task, I do not want to impute any missing values, as this could lead to the misrepresentation of movie profitability in the dataset. Therefore, I will drop all the missing entries from the dataset, and choose to work with a smaller and pure subset of the original dataset.

In [6]:
# Drop the missing entries and reset the index
df = df.dropna()
df.reset_index(drop = True, inplace=True)

2.1.3 Cleaning the Genres Feature¶

Furthermore, there are 745 unique genres in the dataset, which would make extracting meaningful information regarding a specific genre fairly difficult. Say we wanted to test the hypothesis that comedies films were always more profitable than romance films. 2.1.5 Preparing the Target Variable¶

2.1.6 Narrowing the Focus of the Dataset¶

The original movie dataset consisted of movie data collected on 5,043 national and international films. Because of this, the dataset contained a vast number of unique instances in many of the feature columns. For instance, the names of the three lead roles in the movie, each had over 1,400 unique instances. This was also the case with the director_name, country, and content_rating columns. While these columns did not have nearly as many unique instances, they were still a nuisance for the classification task.

As a result of the vast number of unique instances in the dataset, when using the keras implementation of a wide and deep network, often the predict method would fail, because the test set would contain an instance that the training set did not.

To solve this problem, and also enhance the target user third party user of this model, I chose to narrow the focus of the dataset towards the following features:

  • Country: U.S. and U.K.
  • Language: English
  • Genres: Comedy, Action, Drama, Adventure, Crime, Biography, and Horror
  • Content Rating: R, PG-13, PG, and G

By narrowing the focus of this dataset, the primary target users becomes U.S. based movie companies like Disney, Warner Bros. and Fox. The focus of this dataset is now aimed towards U.S. based movies, where the industry is largest and the algorithm is most applicable.

2.1.7 Description of the Final Dataset¶

The final dataset used for the implementation of this wide and deep network consists of 21 categorical and numeric features collected of 3,077 US movies. The dataset contains 5 categorical features and 16 continuous features. A description of each feature and its corresponding variable type is detailed below.

  • color: Movie color. Black and white or color. Categorical.
  • num_critic_for_reviews: Number of critics that reviewed the movie. Continuous.
  • duration: Time duration of the movie. Continuous.
  • director_facebook_likes: Number of facebook likes the director has. Continuous.
  • actor_3_facebook_likes: Number of facebook likes the 3rd lead role actor has. Standard Scaled. Continuous.
  • actor_1_facebook_likes: Number of facebook likes the 1st star role actor has. Continuous.
  • genres: Genre of the movie. Genres include Comedy, Action, Drama, Adventure, Crime, Biography, Horror. Categorical.
  • num_voted_users: Number of users who voted positively on the movie. Continuous.
  • cast_total_facebook_likes: Number of facebook likes the cast as a whole has. Continuous.
  • num_user_for_reviews: Number if users who reviewed the movie. Continuous.
  • language: Language of the movie. English. Categorical.
  • country: Country the movie was made in. US. or U.K. Categorical.
  • content_rating: Movie Rating. Ratings include PG-13, PG, G, R, and GP. Categorical.
  • budget: Movies Budget. Continuous.
  • title_year: Year the movie came out. Continuous.
  • actor_2_facebook_likes: Number of facebook likes the 2nd lead role actor has. Continuous.
  • imdb_score: Moive IMDB score. Continuous.
  • aspect_ratio: Movie aspect ratio. Continuous.
  • movie_facebook_likes: Number of facebook likes the moive has. Continuous.
  • class: Target variable. 1 if the movie grossed more than its budget, 0 if the movie did not gross more than its budget.

2.2 Cross-Product Feature Selection¶

In choosing columns to transform into cross-product features, we must consider the correlation amongst the features. Ideal feature candidates to transform into cross-product features are features that are likely correlated in light of our classification task, thus make sense to be compressed into a single feature and memorized by the wide branch of the network. That is, what features should be memorized by the wide branch of the network to better predict the profitability of a movie. For the cross-product feature selection I have chose to create 2 cross-product features.

The first features I selected to cross are the GENRE and CONTENT_RATING of the movie. I believe these features makes sense to cross, as the combination of the two possibly correlates to the profitability of a movie. For example a PG rated comedy might appeal to a greater portion of the population than an R rated horror movie, and therefore have a higher profitability because more people are likely to buy tickets and see the movie.

The second features I selected to cross are the LANGUAGE of the movie and COUNTRY it was made it. I believe these are likely correlated to the profitability of a movie, because for example a movie in English made in America, where the movie industry is large, is probably going to generate a greater profit than a movie in English made in the U.K., where the film industry is likely smaller than in the U.S.

2.3 Performance Evaluation Metric¶

In choosing an appropriate evaluation metric to evaluate this algorithms performance, it is important to first understand the algorithm's classification task. The classification task for this algorithm, as stated in the business case, is to predict whether a movie will gross more or less than its original budget. Also, in the business case it is stated that, the algorithm needs to achieve greater accuracy than the current industry standard which is roughly 51%.

In really looking into the classification task of this algorithm, the focal point is to predict if a moive is going to be profitable before the film is made. Thus, studios, producers, and investors, could use this algorithm to decide whether or not to invest in making a movie, before the fact. Let's consider a simple example to bring to light the evaluation metric that most suits this algorithm. Say Warner Bros. is going to make the next Batman, and they want to decide if they should make a fourth Batman or lay it to rest. Since the are a giant corporate Hollywood studio, obviously the question they will ask is, will the movie make money. Using our algorithm, they put in the moives budget, rating, genre, ect..., and the algorithm predicts the movie will gross more than its original budget, and therefore be profitable. Great! Warner Bros makes the movie, sinks millions of dollars into the film, and no one wants to see a fourth Batman, the movie tanks, and Warner Bros loses all the money they invested into making the film. This example illustrates the case of our algorithm predicting a false positive, or predicting the movie would be profitable when in fact it will not be, and this the algorithm's greatest pitfall.

Thus, the most appropriate performance evaluation metric for this algorithm is precision. We want our algorithm to be a precise as possible at identifying movies that will gross more than their original budget. An algorithm with higher precision in turn will predict a lower number of false positives, which is what we want to minimize here. However, optimizing precision comes at the price of lower recall. An algorithm that has higher recall attempts to reduce the number of false negatives predicted by the algorithm. For the use case of this algorithm, predicting false negatives is better than predicting false positives, which becomes apparent in considering the following example.

Again, Warner Bros. wants to make another movie, we'll say Harry Potter this time. They again use our algorithm, and our algorithm predicts the movie will not gross more than its original budget, and therefore will not be profitable. Thus, Warner Bros. decides not to make the movie. It turns out Disney, who does not use our algorithm, makes the movie instead and makes a profit, i.e. our algorithm predicted a false negative. While Warner Bros. missed out on a potential profitable opportunity, they did not lose any money by following our algorithms advice.

In really simple terms precision is wanting to be extra certain about a prediction, and recall is not wanting to miss out, and for this case being certain is paramount.

Therefore, PRECISION is the appropriate metric in which to evaluate this algorithm's performance, which is defined mathematically as the number of true positives divided by the number of true positives plus the number of false positives predicted by the algorithm, or:

$$ Precision = \frac{True\hspace{1mm} Positives} {True\hspace{1mm} Positives\hspace{1mm} + \hspace{1mm}False\hspace{1mm}Positives}$$

Also, essential in choosing an appropriate evaluation criteria is the class distribution of the dataset. Observing the class distribution of the dataset will also shed light on how to evaluate the performance of an algorithm. Algorithms that evaluate datasets containing a large class imbalance often need to be evaluated differently than algorithms that evaluate datasets with uniform class distribution.

2.4 Method for Dividing Data into Train and Test Splits¶

In choosing an appropriate method for dividing the dataset into training and testing splits, two characteristics of the dataset should be taken into account. The first being the size of the dataset, meaning the number of instances we have data on, and the second being how the data would likely be obtained and used in the algorithm in practice.

In addressing the size of the dataset, after preparing the data, I am left with 3,077 instances in the dataset. Due to the small amount of instances in the dataset, K-Fold cross validation would be the appropriate method to use to divide the data into training and testing splits. K-Fold cross validation efficiently uses small amounts of data to train and test an algorithm by diving the data into K number of folds, training the algorithm on K-1 folds, and testing the algorithm on the remaining fold. Therefore, even though the dataset has a limited number of instances, our algorithm will still be trained and tested over vast amounts of data. Thus, K-Fold cross validation will efficiently use the small amount of data in this dataset to adequately train and test the algorithm.

Next addressing how this algorithm would be used in practice. In practice, a movie studio, producer, or investor, would likely place the feature data regarding the movie they are considering making into this algorithm to predict whether or not the movie would be profitable. Thus single instances will likely be placed into the algorithm and predicted upon. Because of this I believe stratification is essential in cross validation technique to accurately represent the class distribution of the dataset as a whole when training and testing the algorithm.

As a result of the above the most appropriate method for dividing the dataset into training and testing splits is Stratified K-Fold cross validation.

3.2 Several Wide and Deep Network Architectures¶

The code below in the create model function contains the architecture for the wide and deep network used for Model 1, Model 2, and Model 3 below which fill the requirement to "create several combined wide and deep networks to classify your data using Keras."

In the models below, you may notice I vary the columns that I cross and a few other model parameters. While I argued that genre and content_rating and language and country are the most appropriate features to cross, for the sake of "creating several models" I though it would be interesting to experiment with various cross product features.

It should be noted when visualizing the performance of the models on the training data and validation data using the keras history return parameter, I am limited to the accuracy metric provided by keras. While this accuracy does not reflect the evaluation metric I chose, precision, for the sake of the visualization it serves it purpose. Notice that in the model statistics the precision of the model is the metric the model is evaluated on.

def create_model(X_train, X_test, X_train_numeric, categorical_feature_columns_ints, cross_columns):
    
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_branch_outputs = []
    
    for cols in cross_columns:
        enc = LabelEncoder()
        X_crossed_train = X_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis = 1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis = 1)
        
        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values, X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
        X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)
        
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1] + 1)
        
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim = N, output_dim = int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length = 1, name = '_'.join(cols) + '_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_branch_outputs.append(x)
        
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
        
    all_branch_outputs = []
        
    for col in categorical_feature_columns_ints:     
        X_ints_train.append( X_train[col].values )
        X_ints_test.append( X_test[col].values )
        
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1)
        
        inputs = Input(shape = (1,), dtype = 'int32', name = col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim = N, output_dim = int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length = 1, name = col + '_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_numeric.shape[1],), sparse = False, name = 'numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units = 20, activation = 'relu',name = 'numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # merge the branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 50,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 25,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 10,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep3')(deep_branch)

    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name = 'concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units = 1,activation = 'sigmoid',name = 'combined')(final_branch)

    model = Model(inputs = all_inputs, outputs = final_branch)
    
    return model, X_ints_train, X_ints_test

3.3 Generalization Performance¶

To investigate the generalization performance of the wide and deep network I will perform an exploratory analysis on the number of deep layers in the wide and deep network and examine the effect that altering the number of layers has on the precision of the model. In the modeling of the various layer networks below, I want to set all other modeling parameters constant, so we can get a pure examine of how the number of layers affects model precision. In choosing the parameters to set constant, lets take the parameters from the best performing model above, Model 2, aside from the cross columns which I will set the cross product columns I argued for in the beginning of the lab. In Model 2, the activation of the deep layers is relu, the activation of the final layer is sigmoid, the optimizer is adagrad, the loss is mean_squared_errir, and the batch size is 10, and the number of epochs is 10. So, in the following network implementations the following parameters will remain constant:

  • cross_columns: [content_rating and genre] and [language and country]
  • Activation of Deep Layers: relu
  • Activation of final Layer: sigmoid
  • Optimizer: adagrad
  • loss: mean_squared_error
  • epochs: 10
  • batch_size = 10

The performance of the various networks below will be measured on their mean precision score using Stratified K-Fold cross validation as argued for in the beginning of the lab.

3.3.1 (1) Deep Layer¶

For the first observation, I will constrain the wide and deep network to only have 1 deep layer with 10 neurons.

In [109]:
def create_model_1_deep_layer(X_train, X_test, X_train_numeric, categorical_feature_columns_ints, cross_columns):
    
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_branch_outputs = []
    
    for cols in cross_columns:
        enc = LabelEncoder()
        X_crossed_train = X_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis = 1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis = 1)
        
        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values, X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
        X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)
        
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1] + 1)
        
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim = N, output_dim = int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length = 1, name = '_'.join(cols) + '_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_branch_outputs.append(x)
        
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
        
    all_branch_outputs = []
        
    for col in categorical_feature_columns_ints:     
        X_ints_train.append( X_train[col].values )
        X_ints_test.append( X_test[col].values )
        
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1)
        
        inputs = Input(shape = (1,), dtype = 'int32', name = col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim = N, output_dim = int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length = 1, name = col + '_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_numeric.shape[1],), sparse = False, name = 'numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units = 20, activation = 'relu',name = 'numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # merge the branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 10, activation = 'relu', name = 'deep3')(deep_branch)

    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name = 'concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units = 1, activation = 'sigmoid',name = 'combined')(final_branch)

    model = Model(inputs = all_inputs, outputs = final_branch)
    
    return model, X_ints_train, X_ints_test

3.4 My Best Wide and Deep Network¶

Above, we explored the effect that altering the number of deep layers in the network has on the precision of the model. Up to this point, we have not really explored too many other model parameters which could boost performance. Below, lets perform a some hyperparameter tuning and see if we can increase the model precision. Because the 5 deep layer network achieved the overall performance, lets stick with a 5 layer model and focus on parameters such as the optimization method, the loss function, the number of epochs, and the batch_size.

Because the purpose of this exploration is to tune hyperparameters I will only run the model for 2 fold cross validation to save time as the point of this exercise is not to better understand generalization performance but to achieve optimal performance through hyperparameter tuning.

To select the optimal parameters that will be used in my best performing model, I will select the parameters which return the highest precision score.

def create_model_optimized(X_train, X_test, X_train_numeric, categorical_feature_columns_ints, cross_columns):
    
    embed_branches = []
    X_ints_train = []
    X_ints_test = []
    all_inputs = []
    all_branch_outputs = []
    
    for cols in cross_columns:
        enc = LabelEncoder()
        X_crossed_train = X_train[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis = 1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis = 1)
        
        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.values, X_crossed_test.values)))
        X_crossed_train = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_crossed_test = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_ints_train.append(X_crossed_train)
        X_ints_test.append(X_crossed_test)
        
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1] + 1)
        
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,),dtype='int32', name = '_'.join(cols))
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim = N, output_dim = int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length = 1, name = '_'.join(cols) + '_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_branch_outputs.append(x)
        
    wide_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
        
    all_branch_outputs = []
        
    for col in categorical_feature_columns_ints:     
        X_ints_train.append( X_train[col].values )
        X_ints_test.append( X_test[col].values )
        
        N = max(X_ints_train[-1]+1)
        
        inputs = Input(shape = (1,), dtype = 'int32', name = col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim = N, output_dim = int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length = 1, name = col + '_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)
        all_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
    all_inputs.append(Input(shape=(X_train_numeric.shape[1],), sparse = False, name = 'numeric_data'))

    x = Dense(units = 20, activation = 'relu',name = 'numeric_1')(all_inputs[-1])
    all_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # merge the branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 100,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 75,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 50,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep3')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 25,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep4')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units = 10,activation = 'relu', name = 'deep5')(deep_branch)
    
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name = 'concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units = 1,activation = 'sigmoid',name = 'combined')(final_branch)

    model = Model(inputs = all_inputs, outputs = final_branch)
    
    return model, X_ints_train, X_ints_test

3.5.2 Reciever Operating Characteristic and Area Under the Curve¶

Below, we are going to look at the Reciever Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve and the Area Under the Curve (AUC) as one method to compare scikit-learn's MLP to my best wide and deep network. ROC curves are useful tools which to aid in selecting classification models based on their performance with respect to the False Positive Rate and True Positive Rate. ROC curves are constructed by shifting the decision threshold of the classifier, and counting the number of True Positives and False Negatives both above and below the threshold. The diagonal of an ROC curve represents random guessing, while a perfect classifier would have a True Positive Rate of 1 and a False Positive Rate if 0, represented in the ROC curve below. Once an ROC curve has been calculated, more information can be derived from the AUC to characterize the classification performance of a model, with a greater AUC commonly indicating a better model[3].

Below, lets compute and graphically examine the ROC and AUC of scikit-learn's MLP and my best wide and deep network.

[3] Raschka, Sebastian & Mirkalili, Vahid. Python Machine Learning.

plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate', fontsize = 10)
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend(loc = 'best', fontsize = 10)
plt.show()

Lets use the ROC curve and AUC to determine which classifier is the better choice for the prediction task at hand. In the ROC curve above I have indicated what the performance of a perfect classifier would look like and also what random guessing would look like.

In examining the ROC curve it is seen that scikit-learn's standard MLP outperformed my best wide and deep network in each fold. That is scikit-learn's standard MLP had ROC curves closer to that of a perfect classifier. Also, the average AUC over the three folds for scikit-learn standard MLP was 0.85, while the average AUC for my best wide and deep network over the same three folds was 0.77. Thus, one observation I could make is that based on the average AUC, scikit-learn's standard MLP is the better classifier.

However, there is much more information to be derived from the ROC curve. The ROC curve is also a useful tool in determining the operating point, or decision threshold of a classifier[4]. For instance, if we wanted an operating point that minimized the number of false positives, the scikit-learn MLP would again be the obvious choice as the ROC curve has the steepest slope in the beginning ranging from 0.0 to 0.2 over the False Positive Rate, which shows the algorithm is classifying a very small number of false positives for the number of true positives over this range.

This example is really apparent in looking at the ROC for fold 3. In examining this particular fold it is seen that the MLP ROC curve actually dips below my best wide and deep network ROC curve at about 0.4 on the False Positive Rate. Even though this is the case, I would still say over this fold the MLP ROC curve still looks like the better curve because it contains the most area underneath it over the range of 0.0 to 0.2 on the False Positive Rate. Meaning that the MLP, over fold 3, is classifying fewer false positives per true positives, than my best wide and deep network.

Thus, scikit-learn's standard MLP is the better classifier for the prediction task at hand.

3.5.3 Statistical Comparision¶

Above, we established that scikit-learn's MLP is the better classifier for the prediction task of this dataset. Next, lets explore if we can statistically prove this as well. When I say statistically, I mean can we say the scikit-learn MLP is the better classifier with confidence greater than 95 %.

To statistically compare the performance of my best wide and deep model versus scikit-learns standard MLP, I am going to perform a T-Test. More specifically, I will approximate the bounds using the folds of the cross fold validation to get a mean and variance of the precision score. I believe this is the most appropriate means of generating confidence intervals because both models were trained using the same data, and therefore across the same instances. For the T-Test I will use a t value of 2.26 and k = 10 (note that this is lowercase k and not capital K, which indicated the number of folds in the cross validation).

If the resulting confidence interval does not include 0, then statistically, with 95 % confidence, we can say that the scikit-learn MLP is the better classifier.

In [183]:
K = 10

skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits = 10, random_state = 1).split(X, y)

precision_score_WD = []
precision_score_SK = []

for i, (train, test) in enumerate(skf):
    X_train = df.iloc[train]
    X_test = df.iloc[test]
    y_train = df['class'].iloc[train].values.astype(np.int)
    y_test = df['class'].iloc[test].values.astype(np.int)
    
    X_train_numeric = X_train[numeric_feature_columns].values
    X_test_numeric = X_test[numeric_feature_columns].values
    
    model, X_ints_train, X_ints_test = create_model_optimized(X_train, X_test, X_train_numeric, categorical_feature_columns_ints, cross_columns)
    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])
    model.fit(X_ints_train + [X_train_numeric], y_train, epochs = 20, batch_size = 100, verbose = 0)
    
    sklearnmlp.fit(X_train_numeric, y_train)
    
    yhat_WD = np.round(model.predict(X_ints_test + [X_test_numeric]))
    yhat_SK = sklearnmlp.predict(X_test_numeric)
    
    precision_WD = precision_score(y_test, yhat_WD)
    precision_SK = precision_score(y_test, yhat_SK)
    
    precision_score_WD.append(precision_WD)
    precision_score_SK.append(precision_SK)

However, from the ROC curve above I believe scikit-learn's MLP is the better classifier for the prediction task of this dataset.

4. T-SNE Embedded Layer Weight Clustering and Visualization¶

In this section we will be exploring clustering techniques applied to the embedding weights of the wide and deep network used in my optimized model with the purpose to derive meaningful information regarding categorical features and their corresponding weights.

For the T-SNE clustering exercise in this section, I chose to keep the parameters of the T-SNE method tame. This is because the embedding weights for various embedded layers in the network is not complex or large scale data by any means. Thus, I did not find it necessary to set the perplexity of the T-SNE method to a large value nor set the number of iterations to a large number. In experimenting with the parameters, I actually found I could derive more meaningful clusters when these parameters were kept low.
